Linear Modeling Results - Positive

The lm() function in R creates a regression model with the given data, and the summary functions reviews the weights and performance measures of the model. The residuals allows us to measure and analyze the difference between prediction and actual results of the linear model. Residuals, along with other factors such as the p-value, are observed and tested to see how well the single-variable linear regression model fits the data.

The amount of golf courses available in each state should be a significant factor when you think about it logically. So to no surprise, the incredibly low p value for both girls and boys data allows us to reject the null hypothesis and claim that errors are correlated.

Based on how far we analyzed the reisuals and regression line, we can say that the number of golf courses open to play in each state is a significant factor that affects golf popularity within that area. The linear regression model seems to be a working fit, but looking at the scatterplot also gives an impression that an exponential regression model might be able to fit the data better. Ultimately, we are still able to conclude that as the number of golf courses increase within an area, so will the number of players.
